  "answer": "Both poems are found in the corpus. 'Larkiyan Parh Rahi Hain Angrezi' is Bang-e-Dara Part 3, ch. 27 (slug: allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8); 'Bachay Ki Dua' is Bang-e-Dara Part 1, ch. 16 (slug: allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c).\n\nTonal comparison:\n\n'Larkiyan Parh Rahi Hain Angrezi' (Part 3, ch. 27) is a short, epigrammatic satirical poem (classified under 'Zarifana' — the humorous/satirical section in Iqbal's own scheme). Its tone is sardonic and ironic. The opening couplet — 'The girls are learning English now / The nation has found the path to salvation' — is deliberately sarcastic: equating English-language education with national salvation is precisely what Iqbal is mocking. The poem continues: 'The Western style is held in view / Eastern customs are deemed a sin.' The critique is not anti-education but anti-mimicry — the uncritical adoption of colonial culture at the cost of Eastern identity. The poem closes with suspended, foreboding irony: 'What scene will this drama show? / The gaze awaits the curtain to rise.' The outcome is withheld, but the tone signals dread rather than hope. The poem is pointed, politically charged, and biting.\n\n'Bachay Ki Dua' (Part 1, ch. 16) is a devotional prayer in a child's voice and could not be more different in register. The tone is tender, luminous, and aspirational. The child prays: 'O God, may my life be like a candle's flare' and 'love the candle of knowledge, and draw ever nigher' — education here is figured as a moth drawn to the light of knowledge, a spiritual and self-elevating act. The poem is oriented toward service: illuminate the world, adorn the homeland (like a flower adorns a garden), champion the poor and weak. It closes in confident supplication, with no antagonism to any cultural identity.\n\nThe key tonal contrast: 'Bachay Ki Dua' treats learning as inner illumination and national-ethical vocation — warm, private, hopeful. 'Larkiyan Parh Rahi Hain Angrezi' treats a specific form of education (English schooling for girls as colonial assimilation) as cultural capitulation — public, ironic, apprehensive. In the first poem, the candle of knowledge is something to love; in the second, Western-style schooling is a drama whose curtain is feared. The divergence also reflects the two parts of Bang-e-Dara: Part 1 is more didactic and devotional; Part 3 is more politically satirical and socially critical. Both poems engage education, but from opposite rhetorical positions — one the intimate aspiration of a child, the other the cutting gaze of a cultural critic.",
